 StyleBox["X",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " \[Element] ",
 StyleBox["A",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "] \[NotEqual] 0.  (How does (7) imply the factorization criterion (6), and \
how is it implied by (6)?)",
 "\n",
 "\t For example, from the memory experiment table, P[",
 StyleBox["Y",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " = 4 | ",
 StyleBox["X",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " = 4] = 11/31, since there are 31 subjects such that ",
 StyleBox["X",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " = 4, and 11 of them remembered 4 numbers that were visually presented. \
However, P[",
 StyleBox["Y",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " = 4] is only 36/171, so that the chance that 4 visual numbers are \
remembered is increased by the occurrence of the event that 4 auditory \
numbers were remembered. Even this one violation of condition (7) is enough \
to show that the random variables ",
 StyleBox["X",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["Y",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " are dependent (that is, not independent). But in general, do you really \
have to check all possible subsets ",
 StyleBox["A",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
