Cell[TextData[{
 "Thus, in our example instead of checking 32\[CenterDot]32 = 1024 possible \
combinations of sets ",
 StyleBox["A",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["B",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", we need only check the factorization of ",
 StyleBox["f",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " for 5\[CenterDot]5 = 25 possible combinations of states ",
 StyleBox["x",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["y",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ".  ",
 "\n",
 "\tIndependence for more than two random variables is explored in the \
exercises.  The basic idea is that several random variables are independent \
if and only if any subcollection of them satisfies factorization of \
intersection probabilities as in formula (6). This also follows if and only \
if the joint p.m.f. factors into the product of the marginals. \n\tWe will \
now look at a series of examples to elaborate on the ideas of joint, \
marginal, and conditional distributions and independence."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.4255676856902*^9, 3.4255676984802*^9}, 
