Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Example 3",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "  If two random variables ",
 StyleBox["X",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["Y",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " are independent and we observe instances of them ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{
     FormBox[
      SubscriptBox["X", "1"],
      TraditionalForm], ",", " ", 
     FormBox[
      SubscriptBox["Y", "1"],
      TraditionalForm]}], ")"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{
     FormBox[
      SubscriptBox["X", "2"],
      TraditionalForm], ",", " ", 
     FormBox[
      SubscriptBox["Y", "2"],
      TraditionalForm]}], ")"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ", ... ,",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{" ", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      FormBox[
       SubscriptBox["X", "n"],
       TraditionalForm], ",", " ", 
      FormBox[
       SubscriptBox["Y", "n"],
       TraditionalForm]}], ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ", what patterns would we expect to find?  \n\tWe will answer the question \
by simulating the list of ",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " pairs.  For concreteness, let ",
 StyleBox["X",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " have the discrete p.m.f. ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "(1) = 1/4, ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "(2) = 1/4, ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "(3) = 1/2 and let ",
 StyleBox["Y",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " have the discrete p.m.f. ",
 StyleBox["q",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "(1) = 5/16, ",
 StyleBox["q",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "(2) = 5/16, ",
 StyleBox["q",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "(3) = 3/8.  The program below simulates two numbers at a time from ",
 StyleBox["Mathematica",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "'s random number generator and converts them to observations of ",
 StyleBox["X",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["Y",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", respectively.  If the random number generator works as advertised, the \
values of ",
 StyleBox["X",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["Y",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " that are simulated should be (or appear to be) independent.  We will then \
tabulate the number of times the pairs fell into each of the 9 categories ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"1", ",", "1"}], ")"}], ",", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"1", ",", "2"}], ")"}], ",", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"1", ",", "3"}], ")"}], ",", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"2", ",", "1"}], ")"}], ",", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"2", ",", "2"}], ")"}], ",", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"2", ",", "3"}], ")"}], ",", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"3", ",", "1"}], ")"}], ",", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"3", ",", "2"}], ")"}], ",", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"3", ",", "3"}], ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]]],
 "  and study the pattern. \n\tThe first two commands simulate individual \
observations from the distributions described in the last paragraph, the \
third uses them to simulate a list of pairs, and the last tabulates \
frequencies of the nine states and presents them in a table. "
}], "Text",
